==English==
===Noun===
'''gerundive'''

#(''in Latin grammar''): a [[verbal]] [[adjective]]

The gerundive does not have a direct equivalent in English, which has the [[gerund]] but not the gerundive. In Latin, the gerundive form implies a sense of necessity. For example, the word [[agenda]] is really a gerundive since it is those "things which ought to be done," not "just things to be done."

<b>Disputed?</b>

The above opening statement - "The gerundive does not have a direct equivalent in English, which has the gerund but not the gerundive" - is debatable.

The Australian <i>Macquarie Dictionary</i> (revised 3rd end) disagrees with that statement. Under meaning #2 of <b>Gerundive</b>, the <i>Macquarie</i> states: "... the English <i>-ing</i> form of a verb when used with an adjectival function". The English <i>gerundive</i>, however, does not include the "obligatory" or "necessity" element contained in the Latin <i>gerundive</i>.

